relationships.comment:
The initial note in the bassus in the mass has been transposed up an octave, altering the melodic interval from the expected 4+ to 5-. This alteration moves the bassus into a more "comfortable" range than it would have been had it strictly adhered to the global transposition of 5-.
Additionally, the final two notes of the superius line in the model were condensed in the mass from two minims to two semiminims.
Because the length of the quoted material in the superius and tenor parts matches, as does the length of the material quoted in the contratenor and bassus parts, this could alternatively be understood as Marle quoting two simultaneous contrapuntal duos, an assertion that would not be made about the material in the model without seeing it through the lens of Marle's quotation. (Since the form does not allow me to select multiple contrapuntal duos, these will be cited separately)
The bassus retains the melodic motion presented in the earlier quotation of this passage (5-). This quotation is a transposition of the earlier quotation of the same passage (4-).

assertions.title: Josquin. Benedicta es

assertions.title: Josquin. Benedicta es
assertions.comment: Here Josquin breaks the chant phrase into two motives, one corresponding to "et mittens" and the other to "sic salutavit". The "et mittens" motive forms a non-imitative duo which is repeated almost immediately by the same voices at the same pitch; the countersubject of this non-imitative duo is shared with the *other* non-imitative cell, as indicated here by the "fuga" entry. See the other relationship for details of the second non-imitative cell.

assertions.title: Josquin. Benedicta es
assertions.comment: The chant motive provides one strand of a homorhythmic four-voice NIm, which becomes a five-voice NIm when repeated through the addition of a fifth strand in the discantus. There is a limited amount of invertible counterpoint in that the chant motive which was in the bassus (but not the lowest voice) is moved up an octave into the contratenor for the second two presentations.

Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: The rhythmicised chant soggetto provides one voice of a two-voice NIm presented four times in different voice pairs. Between the third and fourth presentations, there are some more fragmentary entrances: the altus in bb. 12-13 has just the cantizans tail-motive, and the quinta pars in bb. 11-14 has a chimeric entrance consisting of the first five notes of the countersubject joined to the last five notes of the chant soggetto; this forms a partial presentation of the NIm with the countersubject in the bassus.

scores.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: The chant is used as the subject of a complex passage involving both fuga and non-imitative duos (recorded in separate relationships). The most extensive entrances are in the tenor and cantus; the other voices take only a three-note head-motive from the chant melody. The combination of the long tenor entrance with the three-note head-motive in the sexta pars forms a miniature imitative duo which is repeated by the cantus and bassus. More significant modular repetition arises from the presence of countersubjects (analysed separately)

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: This is the simpler of the two non-imitative modules in which the chant soggetto participates in this passage

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: This is a *3-voice* NIm with two presentations. The top voice has a three-note head-motive derived from the chant; the middle voice is an independent motive consisting of a rising fourth followed by a cantizans cadence; the bottom voice begins with the same three-note head-motive (rhythmicised differently) followed by a motive which engages in voice-exchange with the middle voice. In the first presentation of the module, the first three notes of the rising-fourth motive complete a statement of the chant soggetto (see the relationship recording details of the fuga in this passage). In the second NIm presentation this motive occurs independently, without the preceding chant segment.

relationships.titleA: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
relationships.comment: This relationship captures only the entrances of the chant-derived soggetto in fuga; see others for the repeating non-imitative modules which it forms with countersubjects.

relationships.titleA: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina

scores.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: As in the previous section there are two substantial entrances of a chant-derived soggetto, and two fragmentary entrances of its three-note head-motive (both in the altus). The latter do not participate in any modular repetition (see other relationship for details of the NIm in this section) and are probably opportunistic entrances, perhaps (hypothetically) the last to be "fitted in" to an existing structure in the compositional process?

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: This is a *3-voice* NIm with *4* different motives. For the purposes of this relationship only the portion of the chant soggetto that participates in the NIm is shown, although in both cases it is part of a longer fuga entrances. Motive 1 (A-G-F) comes from the chant at "-gris medi-"; motive 2 (G-F-E-C-D) is always heard in one of the bass voices, followed by tenorizans or basizans motion; motive 3 (A-B-C-A) is usually heard in an inner voice; motive 4 is a decorated cantizans cadence. We hear two different three-voice combinations of these four motives in alteration: first 1+2+3, then 2+3+4, then repeat. In other words, motives 2+3 are heard each time, in combination either with the soggetto (motive 1) or with the cantizans cadence (motive 4)

relationships.titleA: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
relationships.comment: This captures the fuga: see other relationship for the simultaneous use of the soggetto in NIms

scores.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: Pieton has concealed the underlying periodicity of this fuga: if we judge from the *second* note of the chant soggetto, this is a PEn(sta) with entrances at the semibreve at the upper fourth. However, the variable length of the subject's first note conceals this regularity, to the extent that the tenor entrance on G which begins first is actually the *comes* to the *dux* represented by the sexta pars entrance on D. The third entrance in the quinta pars is fragmentary.

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: The first four notes of the chant participate in a small NIm with a countersubject consisting of a falling third + rising fourth. The first presentation is complicated by offsetting the countersubject by one minim. The second exchanges the parts in ic12.

relationships.titleA: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
relationships.comment: The chant melody is ornamented as in the Josquin Benedicta es, with the insertion of a G between the B and A of the original chant melody (C-B-G-A-G) complicating its simple descent of a fourth (C-B-A-G)

scores.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina

assertions.title: Pieton Loyset: Benedicta es coelorum regina
assertions.comment: The chant soggetto is in the cantus, beneath which the other voices engage in stretto fuga based on falling fourths and rising thirds; this pattern automatically generates imitations in ic12, permitting entrances at the lower octave and upper fifth. Following the end of the chant soggetto in the cantus, the complete three-voice fuga lattice plus the free continuations that follow each of its entrances is repeated at the same pitch, forming a *3-voice* NIm.

relationships.comment: This portion of Willaert's double canon arguably quotes (in twofold augmentation) one of the two soggetti from Josquin's setting of "Preces nostras", although the motive in question is sufficiently generic that this is arguable. The other subject from this section of the Josquin was already used in the first point of imitation.
The first presentations of the borrowed NIm in Willaert are nearly exact; the later entrances of the countersubject omit one of its notes, simplifying G-Bb-A-G to G-A-G.

assertions.title: Willaert. Missa Mente tota (Kyrie)
assertions.comment: This segment of the double canon is heard only once (it is not repeated by the lower voices) due to its proximity to the final cadence of the section.

assertions.title: Willaert. Missa Mente tota (Kyrie)
assertions.comment: Within the context of the double-canon, Willaert contrives to quote Josquin's NIm in two different ways.  The initial canonic entrances of the borrowed subject (tenor/bassus) are accompanied by the borrowed countersubject in the free voices (contratenor secundus/vagans). The second set of canonic entrances (discantus/contratenor primus) overlap with the tail of the canon in the lower voices, and Willaert concludes the canonic phrase with the countersubject so that the overlap of the voice pairs produces two more presentations of the NIm (inverted and transposed). The end of the canonic phrase in the upper voices accordingly produces two final entrances of the countersubject without the accompanying subject.

assertions.title: Josquin. Mente Tota
assertions.comment: This is one voice of a NIm in Josquin's motet; the other subject is not selected as it is not borrowed here (it was used on its own as a countersubject in Willaert's first point of imitation).

assertions.title: Josquin. Mente Tota
assertions.comment: The subject ends with a cantizans cadence, the countersubject with a tenorizans cadence. Josquin first presents the subject and countersubject as singletons, then in NIm combination. Two more presentations of the NIm flex the subject and retain only the tail of the countersubject (it is joined to a new head-motive, not borrowed and so not indicated here).

assertions.title: Benedicta es,cælorum Regina
assertions.comment: The first entrance in the altus is flexed and the final entrance in the same voice is truncated; the others are strict. It's interesting that Mouton's treatment of the chant in this secunda pars is usually fairly straightforward contrapuntally, with the exceptions of the more complex passages of fuga here and at "quo salvantur omnia" (b. 105). Is this a reflection of the importance of these parts of the text, or is it simply motivated musically by these chant fragments being easier to form into fuga?

Morales turns a brief fuga duo from Josquin into an extended ID + NIm presentation.

assertions.title: Morales. Missa Benedicta es (Gloria)
assertions.comment: This passage basically consists of four presentations of an imitative duo, plus one extra entrance (tenor, bb. 67-69). The first two presentations of the duo also include a non-imitative tail in the lower voice. The third presentation of the duo is inverted (ic12) and flexed. Not recorded in the data are two entrances of a secondary motive in the upper voices of bb. 64-66: this motive resembles the tail of the main subject in diminished rhythmic values, and it is also identical to the motive treated in fuga in bb. 22-28 of this movement (and analogous places in other mvts.)
